DOCUMENT();       

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl",
           "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
           "PGgraphmacros.pl"
           );
       
TEXT(beginproblem()); # standard preamble to each problem.

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(2,4,2);
$b = random(3,5,2);
$p = random(2,3,1);
$ans1 = $a**$p;
$ans2 = $b**$p;

BEGIN_TEXT
Question 2:
$BR $SPACE $BR
Is the function below exponential? $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\(  m(t)= \left( $a \cdot $b^t \right)^$p \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
If so, write the function in the form \( m(t)=ab^t \) and enter the values you find for \( a \) and \( b \) in the indicated blanks below.  If the function is NOT EXPONENTIAL, enter $BBOLD NONE $EBOLD in BOTH blanks below.
$BR
$SPACE
$BR
\( a = \) \{ ans_rule(10) \} \( \ \ \ \ \ \ \) and \( b = \) \{ ans_rule(10) \}

END_TEXT


ANS(fun_cmp($ans1,vars=>['N','O','E']) );
ANS(fun_cmp($ans2,vars=>['N','O','E']) );

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
Yes \( m(t) \) is exponential, and we can rewrite this in standard form, \( m(t)=ab^t \),
$BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE 
\( m(t) = \left( $a \cdot $b^t \right)^{$p} \) $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( = $a^{$p} \cdot \left( $b^t \right)^{$p} \) $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( = $ans1 \cdot $b^{$p t} \) $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( = $ans1 \cdot \left( $b^{$p} \right)^t \) $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE
\( = $ans1 \left( $ans2 \right)^t \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
so \( a = $ans1 \), $SPACE \( b = $ans2 \).
$BR
END_SOLUTION


ENDDOCUMENT();   # This should be the last executable line in the problem.